        target="_blank" data-popup
                ><span class="inline-share-count inline-share-count-linkedin"></span><span class="inline-share-btn-label inline-share-btn-label-linkedin">LINKEDIN</span></a><span
        class="inline-share-btn inline-share-btn-comments"
        data-share-method="comments"
        data-uotrack="InlineShareCommentsBtn"><span class="inline-share-count inline-share-count-comments"></span><span class="inline-share-btn-label inline-share-btn-label-comments">COMMENT</span></span><span
        class="inline-share-btn inline-share-btn-email"
        data-share-method="email"
        data-uotrack="InlineShareEmailBtn"><span class="inline-share-count inline-share-count-email"></span><span class="inline-share-btn-label inline-share-btn-label-email">EMAIL</span></span><span
         class="inline-share-btn inline-share-btn-more"
         data-share-method="facebook"
         data-uotrack="InlineShareMoreBtn"><span class="inline-share-count inline-share-count-more"></span><span class="inline-share-btn-label inline-share-btn-label-more">MORE</span></span></div></div><p>John Green's movie business is revving up again.</p><p>On Thursday, 12 days before the DVD version of "The Fault in Our Stars" arrives in stores, Indianapolis author <a href="https://twitter.com/realjohngreen/status/507559480750395392" title="https://twitter.com/realjohngreen/status/507559480750395392">Green tweeted</a> that an upcoming film adaptation of his novel "Paper Towns" has a director.</p><div id="module-position-NiiE31YTFT4" class="story-asset embed-asset"><div class="embed"><blockquote class="twitter-tweet" lang="en"><p>EXCITING ANNOUNCEMENT: The Paper Towns movie will be directed by the brilliant <a href="https://twitter.com/jakeschreier">@jakeschreier</a>, who previously made &amp;quot;Robot and Frank.&amp;quot;</p>— John Green (@realjohngreen) <a href="https://twitter.com/realjohngreen/status/507559480750395392">September 4, 2014</a></blockquote><script async="true" src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"><!-- comment --></script></div></div><p>New York University graduate Jake Schreier will direct "Paper Towns," which follows his 2012 debut <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9jZlSfsE730" title="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9jZlSfsE730">"Robot &amp; Frank."</a></p><div id="module-position-NiiE31Z8az8" class="story-asset embed-asset"><div class="embed"><iframe width="560" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/9jZlSfsE730?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="true"><!--iframe--></iframe></div></div><p>Published in 2008, "Paper Towns" is a mystery based on an "average" teenage boy from Orlando, Fla., who pines for an "exceptional" teenage girl. The girl goes missing, and the boy follows clues to pursue her.</p><p>Nat Wolff, who portrayed Isaac in "The Fault in Our Stars," has the male lead -- Quentin "Q" Jacobsen -- in "Paper Towns."</p><p>Filmmakers have yet to cast the female lead, Margo Roth Spiegelman.</p><div id="module-position-NiiE31ZRAFk" class="story-asset gallery-asset"><div class="galleries embedded_story hasendslate"
